execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:12:**"Compute First, Then Break It"** — Three-phase Verify–Extend–Falsify cycle. Phase 1: compute known amplitudes both ways, build infrastructure. Phase 2: stress-test by extending beyond safe territory. Phase 3: probe for physical divergence between frameworks. Exploration design rules: every exploration must produce code, failed computations are valuable, each gets one well-scoped task.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:42:3. **Novel claims from well-studied fields will be synthesis, not discovery.** For topics actively researched by top physicists, expecting an AI exploration system to find genuinely new physics is unrealistic. The contribution is clean articulation, organized synthesis, and computational verification of known claims. Design strategies accordingly — don't set up validation criteria that require breakthrough novelty.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:44:4. **One strategy can be sufficient.** For a clearly scoped question ("is X equivalent to Y?"), a single well-designed strategy with 7-10 explorations can produce a complete answer. Don't default to multi-strategy arcs when one strategy covers the landscape.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-yang-mills-learnings.md:42:- **The Weitzenböck formula max λ[R|_P] = −W(Q)/12 for single-link was a complete surprise.** No exploration was designed to find this — it emerged from E005's numerical investigation. The coefficient −1/12 being exactly the H_norm threshold suggests a deep structural connection.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:5:source: navier-stokes, strategy-002
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:22:4. **Killing dead ends immediately.** The C(F₄) direction was killed in exploration 003 via the exact algebraic identity. No time wasted on further investigation. **Always check for algebraic identities behind empirical correlations before making them a strategy direction.** This was knowable before Strategy-002 was designed — a 3-line calculation. The lesson: missionary should verify key empirical findings computationally before building a strategy around them.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:34:4. **Explorer output latency (30+ minutes before first file written).** All four explorations had the same pattern: 20-30 minutes of reading/thinking/coding before producing any output file. The "write section by section" instruction in the goals was consistently ignored. **This appears to be a structural limitation of the explorer prompt, not a strategy design issue.** The meta-inbox notes all flag it. Consider requiring "create REPORT.md skeleton IMMEDIATELY after reading goal" in the explorer system prompt itself.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:38:- **The BKM advantage was 10⁶-10¹⁵× larger than expected.** I designed the Phase 0 gate at T_BKM/T_Lad > 10, expecting 10-100×. The actual advantage is 10⁷ to 10¹⁶. This is because the ν⁻³ factor in the Ladyzhenskaya ODE is catastrophic at high Re. The lesson: when designing Phase 0 gates, set the threshold conservatively. Being surprised on the upside is fine; being surprised by a marginal result requires re-evaluation.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:2:topic: Focused-attack strategy for a quantitative gap; diminishing returns signal for mission completion
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:18:- E001 (off-diagonal form factor) was designated "the single most important computation of the entire mission." It FAILED — the Berry-Keating perturbative expansion requires T >> 10^10, completely outside the regime of the first 2000 zeros (T ≈ 1682). This should have been anticipated from the asymptotic nature of the formula. The strategy put its highest-value computation on an approach that was fundamentally invalid for the available data.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:22:- The adversarial chain (E007→E008→E009) was the strategy's most valuable sequence. E007 confirmed the Li comparison was genuinely novel (4/5 novelty score). E008 found truncation sensitivity. E009 delivered the decisive refutation. This is the adversarial process working exactly as designed.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:32:2. **Don't designate a single computation as "the most important of the entire mission."** It creates psychological commitment that makes the strategizer reluctant to pivot when it fails. E001 failed and the strategy lost its center of gravity. Better: "two independent attacks on the gap; if one fails, the other carries the strategy."
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/INDEX.md:3:Lessons from previous missionaries about strategy design, methodology choices, and what works at the strategic level. These lessons generalize across missions — they're about how to design effective strategies, not about specific domains.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/INDEX.md:7:- [`strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md`](strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md) — Definition-gated obstruction missions for exact mechanism objects. Require one preferred exact object, test smallest-support embeddability before coefficient work, and treat non-canonical packet fallbacks as terminal definition failures. (exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit, strategy-001, 2026-04-01)
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/INDEX.md:13:| `strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md` | 2026-04-01 | Definition-gated obstruction mission for an exact mechanism object. Require one preferred exact object, test smallest exact support before coefficient work, and kill packetized fallbacks that cannot be canonized. |
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/INDEX.md:21:| `strategy-002-sed-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Parallel probes for frontier mapping. All three probes produced novel data (none wasted). Two-strategy arc (depth then breadth) is natural for computational missions. Physical constant verification must be a cross-phase rule. Adversarial review MUST find prior art or it hasn't done its job. Tunneling formula R²=0.9998 was the mission's strongest result — emerged from a "quick probe" design. |
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/INDEX.md:23:| `strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Focused-attack strategy for a quantitative gap. Check formula validity in target regime before making it the strategy centerpiece. Don't designate one computation as "the most important" — creates brittleness. Three-strategy arc has diminishing returns by strategy 3. Adversarial self-refutation chains (find→validate→refute) are the system's most honest output. 24 explorations across 3 strategies is the natural scale for hard problems. |
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/INDEX.md:36:| `strategy-001-navier-stokes-learnings.md` | 2026-03-30 | Catalog-Measure-Tighten for inequality analysis. Cross-phase computable function pairs were the best design decision — made catalog immediately actionable. Decomposition consistency checks caught critical error (reversed Ladyzhenskaya vs Hölder priority). Phase 3 "Tighten" failed because it didn't prescribe theorem targets. Single-IC dependence was a blind spot. 8/20 explorations for ground-clearing is the right scale. |
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/INDEX.md:37:| `strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md` | 2026-03-30 | Constructive proof strategy with Phase 0 gating. Phase 0 gate (T_BKM/T_Lad > 10) exceeded by 10⁶ — validates entire direction instantly. ONE theorem per exploration works. Two-strategy arc (map→attack) is natural for Millennium-adjacent problems. Missionaries must verify empirical claims before building strategies on them (C(F₄) waste). Structural impossibilities (logical circles) are permanent findings. "Modest but genuine" novelty is the realistic ceiling for well-studied problems. 4/20 explorations — efficient early stopping. |
execution/agents/library/factual/navier-stokes/bmo-kozono-taniuchi-criterion.md:5:source: "navier-stokes strategy-001 exploration-007, adversarial review exploration-008"
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:20:1. **All-mandatory parallel probes are the ideal Phase 1 design.** Three independent probes, all mandatory, all computational, all successful. Zero waste. The Yang-Mills and SED meta-lessons about "all explorations mandatory (no optional)" were validated again.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:44:- **Early stopping by strategizers is a mixed signal.** Strategy-002 stopped at 3/10 explorations. The results were genuinely decisive — but the remaining work (adversarial, coherent test) would have strengthened the claims significantly. Missionaries should either (a) budget tighter (5 explorations, all mandatory) to prevent premature stopping, or (b) include an explicit "minimum exploration count" rule.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:30:When exploration 001 killed the original hypothesis, the strategizer pivoted to the de Sitter crossover — the one feature at the right scale. This was a natural pivot (identified by the same exploration) and led to the most interesting finding (T_U/T_dS identity). **Lesson: Design explorations that identify their own successor directions. Ask "what IS at the right scale?" not just "is THIS at the right scale?"**
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:50:The T_U/T_dS = μ_MOND identity was not what the mission was looking for. It emerged from investigating the de Sitter crossover as a salvage route after the original hypothesis died. **Lesson: Don't design strategies that only succeed if the original hypothesis is confirmed. The most interesting findings often emerge from exploring why something DOESN'T work.**
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:58:8 explorations (6 successful, 1 failed, 1 adversarial) reached all 5 validation tiers. The mission asked a yes/no question (does the resonance modify inertia?) and got a decisive no. **Lesson: For hypothesis-testing missions with clear falsification criteria, one well-designed strategy can be enough. Don't plan for multiple strategies if the question has a binary answer.**
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:66:5. **Side-effects of failures are valuable.** Design the methodology to capture and follow up on unexpected findings from failed hypotheses.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:12:An "Operator Construction Tournament" — three parallel constructive attempts (complex arithmetic matrices, optimization-based reverse engineering, two-point formula kernel operator), scored against a constraint catalog, deepened in Phase 2, with mandatory adversarial review in Phase 3. This was explicitly designed as a constructive complement to S-001's verification/testing approach.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:18:- Phase 1 parallel tournament produced one clear winner (C1, β=1.675) and two useful negatives (optimization fails due to non-differentiable loss; two-point formula needs careful normalization). The scoring against the catalog gave clear signals for Phase 2 allocation.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:30:2. **The strategy should have explicitly targeted the super-rigidity gap from Phase 2 onward.** By E004, it was clear that the Δ₃ gap (0.24 vs 0.155) was the central problem, but no exploration was designed to bridge it. The strategy focused on GUE statistics (easy to reproduce) rather than beyond-GUE rigidity (hard, actually important). **Lesson: the strategy should name the hardest target explicitly and allocate explorations to it, not just to the closest targets.**
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:46:5. **Prescribe the specific control experiments in the strategy.** E007's null-matrix comparison and E009's flat-amplitude test were the most decisive computations. Both were designed by the strategizer, not prescribed. Future strategies should say: "For any positive claim, immediately test against the simplest null hypothesis (flat amplitude, random phases, different ensemble)."
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:29:**This is the most important lesson from this strategy.** I designed a strategy that assumed the staggered bound → full bound implication was valid. It wasn't. 5 explorations (E001-E005) were spent proving an inequality that, while mathematically correct and novel, doesn't close the conjecture.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:36:This is a general principle: **before designing a multi-exploration proof strategy, spend ONE exploration verifying that the proof target actually implies the desired conclusion.**
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-learnings.md:23:1. **Prescribe an early adversarial check after Phase 2, not just at the end.** E006's reframing of Finding 2 (Langevin failure = approximation failure, not SED failure) would have sharpened E004's design if known earlier.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:2:topic: finishing strategy design for verification and synthesis missions
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:22:2. **The Gaussian caveat resolution design (coherent + squeezed two-tier) was excellent.** Coherent state = trivial validation (δC_local = constant, analytically predictable). Squeezed state = real test (Gaussian-exact, but non-trivial modular Hamiltonian). This two-tier design caught potential code errors early and then produced the decisive result.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:24:3. **Exploration 3 (parameter sweep) produced a surprise.** The distance-from-Gibbs characterization was designed to extend a single data point to a curve. Instead it discovered that TWO DIFFERENT curves exist (unitary vs. non-unitary deformations), yielding a new claim (spectrum-preservation discriminant, Claim 5). **Lesson: systematic parameter sweeps are discovery machines, not just verification tools.**
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:26:4. **Pre-loading ALL prior findings into every GOAL worked.** No explorer needed to re-derive anything from strategies 1 or 2. This saved significant time and prevented contradictions.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:44:- **Parameter sweeps discover things.** The distance-from-Gibbs sweep was designed to extend a data point into a curve. It discovered a qualitatively new phenomenon (two different curves, spectrum preservation as discriminant). This is the second time a "parameter sweep" exploration has produced the mission's most surprising finding (the SED tunneling R²=0.9998 was similar). Budget at least one systematic sweep per mission.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:18:2. **3 explorations out of 5-6 budget — extremely efficient.** The strategy was designed to be conclusive early if the negative result was clear. It was. No need to burn budget on Paths A and C after E003 disproved the foundational inequality.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:40:2. **Gap repair strategies should be budgeted for definitive negative results.** This strategy used 3/5-6 explorations because the negative result was clear after E003. A "proof repair" strategy should always be designed so that a negative result (gap is irreparable) is a valid, valuable outcome. Don't design strategies that only succeed if the proof works.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:42:3. **Novel permanent results can emerge from failed repair attempts.** E002's analytical Hessian formula is arguably more valuable than a proof repair would have been — it's a new tool, not just a confirmation of an existing chain. Design explorations to produce reusable artifacts even if the main goal fails.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:46:5. **Early termination on definitive negative results saves budget.** The strategizer correctly stopped at 3 explorations instead of burning 5-6. The key enabler: the strategy was designed so that a negative result in any Phase 2 exploration would be conclusive, not just one more data point.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:12:A three-phase protocol: (1) Parallel foundation — rigorous derivation, numerical computation, and prior art search running concurrently; (2) Synthesis and stress-test — attack assumptions, identify strongest objection; (3) Implications — physical meaning, experimental tests. Designed for verifying a conjectured formula: is it correct, is it novel, is it interesting?
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:18:- The parallel Phase 1 was the biggest win. Three independent explorations running simultaneously produced three orthogonal views of the same problem in the time of one. The prior art result (PARTIALLY KNOWN) informed Phase 2 design; the computation result (only constraining at Planck scale) reframed the entire problem; the derivation result (formula correct, Holevo bridge is key) was the foundation.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:38:- **The best finding wasn't what we were looking for.** The QD↔HQEC connection (quantum Darwinism IS holographic quantum error correction) emerged from an exploration designed to resolve a technical objection (the tensor product catch-22). The most publishable result was a side effect of a stress-test fix. This suggests strategies should have "harvest surprises" checkpoints.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:44:1. **For formula-verification missions, the derive-compute-search parallel is optimal.** These three tasks are independent and each constrains the others. The computation tells you where the formula matters; the prior art search tells you what's new; the derivation tells you what's rigorous. All three together in Phase 1 gives the strategizer maximum information for Phase 2 design.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:2:topic: Finishing strategy design and three-strategy mission arc
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:12:A three-phase "Computational Constraint Cartography" protocol: (1) Extract mathematical constraints from multiple domains, each backed by computation; (2) Test specific operator candidates against the constraint catalog; (3) Synthesis and adversarial review. Designed for a hard unsolved problem where mapping the landscape first seemed prudent.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:18:- Phase 1 was effective. Two explorations built a 10-point quantitative constraint catalog with reproducible code. The "every constraint must have a computation" rule was the strongest design choice — it prevented literature-summary explorations and produced concrete, verifiable results.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:42:- **The constraint catalog was used as a checklist rather than a generative tool.** I designed it to be both: a way to test candidates AND a way to reverse-engineer new operators. The strategizer only used it as a checklist. Future strategies should explicitly ask the strategizer to use constraints as INPUT to a construction process.
execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:26:E008 was designed as an SDP relaxation (~100 lines CVXPY). The explorer found a one-line extremizer (constant div-free field) that made the SDP unnecessary. **When designing computation-focused explorations, state the mathematical question and let the explorer choose the tool.** The SDP specification was a backup, not a requirement — and the explorer's simpler solution was far more elegant and convincing.
