runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1514:The strategizer correctly deviated from the strategy to insert Phase 1b/1c (4 explorations following leads from Phase 1) before the adversarial review. This was good judgment — the adversarial review would have just flagged these as unexplored leads. **Future strategies should include a "Lead Pursuit" phase between measurement and adversarial review as a prescribed option:** "If Phase 1 surfaces promising leads, the Strategizer may run up to N additional explorations before Phase 2, provided each is a single-task, literature-or-computation goal."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1517:E009 (adversarial review) correctly identified Claim 5 as the weakest link. E010 (targeted test) definitively showed the Beltrami mechanism doesn't generalize. Without this sequence, the final report would have overclaimed the Beltrami connection. **Always budget at least 1 exploration after the adversarial review for targeted follow-up on the weakest identified claim.** This should be prescribed in the methodology, not left to strategizer judgment.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1532:4. Add a "direction status" tracking table that the strategizer maintains and updates after each exploration (OPEN/CLOSED/PROMISING/EXHAUSTED for each direction)
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1574:### The strategizer's decision to compress Phase 1 was correct and should be anticipated
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1575:The strategy allocated 3 explorations to Phase 1. The strategizer used 2 — E001 was so thorough (with pre-loaded adversarial context) that E003 became redundant. The saving was reinvested into Phase 2.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1588:The Tsirelson non-unistochastic question is a well-defined computational problem (enumerate ISPs on 4×4 stochastic matrix, apply causal locality, optimize CHSH). The strategizer identified it in E005 as the "single most important open question" but didn't run it. The strategy should have anticipated that for reformulation programs, the most interesting computation is not "verify the correspondence" but "test the extension beyond the correspondence."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1590:**Generalizable lesson:** For reformulation/framework analysis missions, include a Phase 2 exploration explicitly targeting: "What computation, if run successfully, would upgrade this reformulation to new physics? Design and run that computation." This is the highest-value question and should not be left to the strategizer's discretion — it should be structurally required.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1593:The strategizer skipped the side-by-side QM↔ISP worked example (Strategy E4) because the gap analysis (ISP erases phases → strictly less informative) answered the equi-informativeness question. This was probably correct, but a concrete computation showing the same qubit system in both formalisms would have been more pedagogically convincing and might have revealed structural details the gap analysis missed.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1602:1. **The strategizer never queried the librarian after E002.** It had enough context from E001-E002 to design all remaining goals without library queries. This suggests that for focused missions with pre-loaded context, the library is most valuable at the start and becomes redundant midway through.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-missionary.log:1606:3. **6 of 8 explorations used.** The strategizer had budget remaining and correctly assessed diminishing returns. Good strategies build in budget slack; great strategizers know when to stop early.
