runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:1694:- **check-bypass-not-just-improve-bottleneck.md** — NEW (vasseur-pressure S2-E005): When a bottleneck tool limits progress, always ask "can we avoid this tool entirely?" before "can we improve it?" Protocol: (1) Can we avoid using this tool at all? (2) Is there a fundamentally different tool for the same job? (3) Can we improve the tool's output? S2-E001 through S2-E005 spent 5 explorations on question 3 (improving CZ or working around it); the strategizer should have asked question 1 after S2-E001 showed all CZ-based routes are tight. Distinct from ask-what-replaces-the-bottleneck (what new bottleneck after reformulation vs. whether to use the tool at all), decomposition-audit-before-attacking-barrier (which step is tight vs. whether the framework is right), and decisive-negative-pivot (when to stop vs. what direction to go).
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:1729:- **allow-explorer-synthesis.md** — Don't over-specify conclusions; specify what to investigate and what format to produce, but leave synthesis conclusions open. Explorers can discover structural patterns (e.g., two-tier tree-vs-loop insight; N²/p ≈ 250-310 ratio; underexploited constraints insight; unexpected no-go theorems) the strategizer didn't anticipate — often the most valuable outputs. **NEW variant: "What would be a breakthrough?" primes explorer for high-value output** without specifying what the answer should be. **NEW variant: "Explain WHY this agrees with [prior result]" elicits novel bonus derivations** — the mechanism explanation is more valuable than the consistency check itself (SED s003-meta-001: symmetry argument from P&C consistency check).
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:1740:- **verify-goal-claims-before-delegating.md** — **[NEW, YM s003-meta-005/s003-007]** Before writing GOAL.md citing a prior result (e.g., "M(Q) ≼ M(I) confirmed by E004"), verify the cited claim actually matches what the exploration found. Two-level fix: (1) strategizer re-reads REPORT.md before citing; (2) GOAL.md includes "first compute X for 3-5 random examples — if it fails, pivot." Prevented two wasted explorations in yang-mills s003. **NEW variant: "verify paper existence before citing"** [vasseur-pressure E003 — "Tran-Yu (2014, AIHP)" doesn't exist; actual program is 5 papers 2015-2021]. Distinct from preload-context (providing findings) and include-trivial-control-checks (validating code).
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:1830:- **thermal-time strategy-001 meta-exploration-001** — Exploration-001 combined a modular Hamiltonian catalog (paper-reading + formalization) with a Fock-space computation. The normalization question (τ=t vs. τ=β·t) arose mid-exploration and was correctly flagged as open rather than resolved — which required a dedicated follow-up exploration (E002). The strategizer note: "When the key question is normalization (a convention question), put it in its own exploration — it requires careful paper-reading that competes with computation time."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:1845:**Relationship to one-task-per-exploration:** This corollary is the pragmatic fallback for when the strategizer nevertheless includes multiple tasks. The ideal is one task; the next best is explicit skip permissions.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:1893:- **thermal-time strategy-001 meta-exploration-003** — The local vs. global modular flow question (does TTH apply K_A for subsystem A, or K_AB for the full system?) was not explicitly resolved until exploration-003. Explorations 001 and 002 implicitly assumed the local interpretation (K_A) and computed its consequences. Exploration-003 discovered that the global interpretation (K_AB) is trivially equivalent to standard QM. The strategizer note: "The literature disambiguation question (local vs. global) should have been in exploration-002 or even exploration-001. We spent two explorations computing assuming the local interpretation without confirming it was Connes-Rovelli's intent."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:1911:- **riemann-hypothesis strategy-001 exploration 006** — The strategizer noted in retrospect: "Real symmetric matrices can only reach GOE (β=1), never GUE (β=2). This is a fundamental constraint I should have mentioned in the goal." The exploration was not wasted (it confirmed the constraints empirically), but a cleaner goal would have pre-scoped the search to complex-valued constructions from the start.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:2031:execution/agents/library/meta/goal-design/check-faithful-support-shrinkage-before-narrowing.md:32:Narrowing can create fake progress. A mission that sounds smaller may still require the entire old object once words like "trigger," "delay," "witness," or "small compared to" are made exact. If the faithful support has not shrunk, the strategizer should spend the turn transferring prior negatives, not pretending a new Phase 1 object exists.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:2096:- **stochastic-electrodynamics strategy-001 exploration 001** — The strategizer pointed the explorer
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:2127:- **riemann-hypothesis strategy-003 exploration-006** — The GOAL.md template specified weight = (log p)² for Berry's diagonal approximation, but the correct Berry (1985) weight is (log p)²/p^m. The 1/p^m factor comes from the squared semiclassical amplitude |A_{p,m}|². Without it, K_primes was ~183 at τ=1 (should be ~1). The explorer caught and corrected this, but it cost debugging time. The strategizer should have checked Berry's original formula before writing the weight expression.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:2133:- **stochastic-electrodynamics strategy-002 exploration-005** — The GOAL.md code snippet included `omega_max=10.0` as a function parameter but the PSD formula body computed `S_F = 2*tau*hbar*omegas**3/m` without the `np.where(..., omegas <= omega_max, ...)` guard. This meant the "no-cutoff" version ran, producing A ≈ 1.6 instead of the correct A ≈ 1.07 (the E001 value). The explorer caught this by re-reading the original E001 code and comparing it line-by-line to the goal template — costing extra time. Had the strategizer tested the template against one known result before pasting it, the bug would have been caught at goal-writing time.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:2160:When a follow-up exploration needs to build on prior results, have the explorer **re-read the actual saved data files** (e.g., `.npz`, `.pkl`, prior REPORT.md) rather than relying on the strategizer's summary of those results. Strategizer summaries can contain transcription errors, incorrect parameter descriptions, or wrong reference values that waste exploration time.
