runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1598:- **check-bypass-not-just-improve-bottleneck.md** — NEW (vasseur-pressure S2-E005): When a bottleneck tool limits progress, always ask "can we avoid this tool entirely?" before "can we improve it?" Protocol: (1) Can we avoid using this tool at all? (2) Is there a fundamentally different tool for the same job? (3) Can we improve the tool's output? S2-E001 through S2-E005 spent 5 explorations on question 3 (improving CZ or working around it); the strategizer should have asked question 1 after S2-E001 showed all CZ-based routes are tight. Distinct from ask-what-replaces-the-bottleneck (what new bottleneck after reformulation vs. whether to use the tool at all), decomposition-audit-before-attacking-barrier (which step is tight vs. whether the framework is right), and decisive-negative-pivot (when to stop vs. what direction to go).
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1623:execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:32:3. **Explorer death rate (4/9 requiring manual completion) is the #1 operational problem.** The strategizer's workaround (manual recovery from computed data) was effective but expensive. The pattern: explorer computes results → enters extended thinking loop → writes skeleton with placeholders → dies. **Lesson: instruct "write each section immediately after its computation, mark [SECTION COMPLETE]" in every goal. Don't let explorers defer writing.**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-hidden-precursor-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1660:Narrowing can create fake progress. A mission that sounds smaller may still require the entire old object once words like "trigger," "delay," "witness," or "small compared to" are made exact. If the faithful support has not shrunk, the strategizer should spend the turn transferring prior negatives, not pretending a new Phase 1 object exists.
