runtime/logs/codex-atlas-far-field-pressure-harmonic-loophole-missionary.log:622:execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:36:4. **Explorer access to papers matters.** The strategy specified "extract formulas from Berry 1985, Bogomolny-Keating 1996." Math Explorers can't access papers (no web). Standard Explorers find abstracts, not equations. The explorer had to reconstruct formulas from fragments and secondary sources, introducing errors. **Lesson: provide the key formulas DIRECTLY in the GOAL.md**, extracted from papers by the strategizer or missionary before launch.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-far-field-pressure-harmonic-loophole-missionary.log:662:The mission has no strategy directories yet, so I’m pulling the most relevant missionary guidance and checking whether a strategizer is already running for this mission before I create anything.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-far-field-pressure-harmonic-loophole-missionary.log:689:| `strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Constructive attack producing novel rigorous result. Adversarial review (E007) after first surprise produced the most important finding (staggered mode tight bound). Original attack vector (RG+BE) correctly abandoned for simpler tighter analysis. 3-exploration proof arc (slack → tight bound → proof) is the natural unit. Prescribe methodology not attack vector — let strategizer pivot. β < 1/6 proved (4× state of art), β < 1/4 with one remaining inequality. |
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-far-field-pressure-harmonic-loophole-missionary.log:690:| `strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Parallel computational probes for regime exploration. All-mandatory parallel probes + pre-loaded context is the highest-efficiency pattern. Adversarial review must be structurally enforced (not just labeled mandatory) — strategizer skipped it. Approximation caveats need built-in resolution paths. Early stopping at 3/10 explorations was mixed: results decisive but claims unverified. Physics errors in GOALs for QFT must specify which symmetry generator. |
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-far-field-pressure-harmonic-loophole-missionary.log:721:The strategizer correctly deviated from the strategy to insert Phase 1b/1c (4 explorations following leads from Phase 1) before the adversarial review. This was good judgment — the adversarial review would have just flagged these as unexplored leads. **Future strategies should include a "Lead Pursuit" phase between measurement and adversarial review as a prescribed option:** "If Phase 1 surfaces promising leads, the Strategizer may run up to N additional explorations before Phase 2, provided each is a single-task, literature-or-computation goal."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-far-field-pressure-harmonic-loophole-missionary.log:724:E009 (adversarial review) correctly identified Claim 5 as the weakest link. E010 (targeted test) definitively showed the Beltrami mechanism doesn't generalize. Without this sequence, the final report would have overclaimed the Beltrami connection. **Always budget at least 1 exploration after the adversarial review for targeted follow-up on the weakest identified claim.** This should be prescribed in the methodology, not left to strategizer judgment.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-far-field-pressure-harmonic-loophole-missionary.log:739:4. Add a "direction status" tracking table that the strategizer maintains and updates after each exploration (OPEN/CLOSED/PROMISING/EXHAUSTED for each direction)
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-far-field-pressure-harmonic-loophole-missionary.log:793:The key prior pattern is clear: proof-improvement missions benefit from an explicit decomposition audit and a direction-status tracker. I’m reading the predecessor reports just enough to preload the exact obstruction context into the first strategy rather than making the strategizer reconstruct it from scratch.
