runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:490:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-navier-stokes-learnings.md:22:4. **Prescribed computation scale.** Requiring ≥4 Reynolds numbers, convergence checks at two resolutions, and ≥5 initial condition types meant results had real statistical weight. The strategizer was disciplined about this.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:491:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-navier-stokes-learnings.md:24:5. **Budget efficiency.** 8 of 20 explorations used. The strategizer correctly stopped when the Phase 3 tightening paths were mapped rather than spending 12 more explorations on diminishing returns. This was the right call — the remaining budget is better spent on a focused constructive strategy.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:494:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-navier-stokes-learnings.md:30:2. **Literature survey should have preceded the spectral Ladyzhenskaya computation.** Exploration 006 (spectral Ladyzhenskaya) was predictably a dead end if you read Tao (2014). The strategizer recognized this in hindsight. **When a direction depends on whether harmonic analysis alone can improve things, check for known obstructions FIRST.**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:498:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-navier-stokes-learnings.md:39:- The strategizer pivoted well when directions failed (spectral Ladyzhenskaya → BKM). But the pivots were reactive, not proactive. The methodology could have structured alternative paths from the start.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:519:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:32:3. **Explorer death rate (4/9 requiring manual completion) is the #1 operational problem.** The strategizer's workaround (manual recovery from computed data) was effective but expensive. The pattern: explorer computes results → enters extended thinking loop → writes skeleton with placeholders → dies. **Lesson: instruct "write each section immediately after its computation, mark [SECTION COMPLETE]" in every goal. Don't let explorers defer writing.**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:524:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:46:5. **Prescribe the specific control experiments in the strategy.** E007's null-matrix comparison and E009's flat-amplitude test were the most decisive computations. Both were designed by the strategizer, not prescribed. Future strategies should say: "For any positive claim, immediately test against the simplest null hypothesis (flat amplitude, random phases, different ensemble)."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:559:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-classicality-budget-learnings.md:26:1. **Nothing major.** The mandatory-explorations-only approach was the right fix for strategy-001's gap problem. The focused scope and clear deliverables for each exploration made the strategizer's job easy.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:560:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-classicality-budget-learnings.md:28:2. **Could have included a "synthesize novel claims" exploration.** The FINAL-REPORT was written by the strategizer without a dedicated synthesis exploration. A synthesis exploration might have caught additional connections between claims (e.g., the de Sitter universality observation deserved more attention).
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:563:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-classicality-budget-learnings.md:34:- **The strategizer's efficiency.** Strategy-001 used 7/10 explorations over an extended period. Strategy-002 used 4/5-6 explorations and completed faster with better-targeted results. Focused strategies with clear deliverables are dramatically more efficient than broad survey strategies.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:568:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-classicality-budget-learnings.md:44:2. **Mandatory > optional for mission-critical requirements.** If the mission says "identify an experimental test," the strategy must say "Exploration C: find an experimental test. This is mandatory." Optional directions get optimized away by strategizers who follow intellectual interest.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:583:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:27:**Strategy execution was efficient:** 6 of 7 explorations used. The strategizer correctly skipped Phase 1 (direction already clear from Phase 0), correctly identified the decoherence lemma as the key proof target, and correctly pivoted when it was falsified.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:608:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:20:**The proof construction was excellent.** The 9D staggered bound was proved in 5 explorations via a novel affine-in-D + Cauchy-Schwarz argument. The strategizer's adaptations were all correct:
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:644:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/INDEX.md:26:| `strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Constructive attack producing novel rigorous result. Adversarial review (E007) after first surprise produced the most important finding (staggered mode tight bound). Original attack vector (RG+BE) correctly abandoned for simpler tighter analysis. 3-exploration proof arc (slack → tight bound → proof) is the natural unit. Prescribe methodology not attack vector — let strategizer pivot. β < 1/6 proved (4× state of art), β < 1/4 with one remaining inequality. |
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:645:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/INDEX.md:27:| `strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Parallel computational probes for regime exploration. All-mandatory parallel probes + pre-loaded context is the highest-efficiency pattern. Adversarial review must be structurally enforced (not just labeled mandatory) — strategizer skipped it. Approximation caveats need built-in resolution paths. Early stopping at 3/10 explorations was mixed: results decisive but claims unverified. Physics errors in GOALs for QFT must specify which symmetry generator. |
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:668:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-yang-mills-learnings.md:32:4. **Lean formalization was again deprioritized.** Three strategies, 30 explorations, zero formalization attempts. The mandate was consistently overridden by the strategizer. Either mandate it as non-negotiable (exploration 9 IS formalization, no exceptions) or remove it from the methodology entirely.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:694:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:30:**Generalizable lesson:** For mechanism-formalization missions, require exactly one preferred exact object and at most one backup. If the strategizer cannot do that, the mission is not ready for quantitative work.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:721:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:16:The strategizer used 4 explorations total (2 Phase 1, 2 Phase 2) and reached a clean conclusion: TTH has no novel testable content for non-relativistic equilibrium systems. The strategizer correctly stopped early rather than padding. Phase 3 was never needed.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:723:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:22:2. **Phased approach with clear completion criteria was effective.** The strategizer knew when Phase 1 was done (modular Hamiltonians computed, normalization resolved) and transitioned cleanly to Phase 2. The criteria prevented both premature and excessive exploration.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:724:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:26:4. **The strategizer was efficient.** 4 explorations to a definitive result is excellent. The REASONING.md shows clear self-correction (catching the wrong baseline comparison after exploration-002).
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:726:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:32:2. **The local-vs-global interpretation question was left too late.** This was THE critical disambiguation, and the strategizer correctly identified it as urgent after exploration-003. But the strategy should have forced this question into Phase 1 as a mandatory milestone. Lesson: for hypothesis-testing missions, interpretation questions must be resolved BEFORE computing consequences.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:730:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:42:- **4 explorations can be sufficient for a definitive conclusion.** If the question is clear and the methodology is right, you don't need 10 explorations. The strategizer's judgment to stop after a clean negative result (rather than padding) was correct.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:744:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:25:**Phase 2 adaptation was critical.** E005 stalled (47 min extended thinking), producing no proof but a KEY reformulation (3×3 matrix). The strategizer correctly deviated from the prescribed sequence (was supposed to do adversarial review next, but there was nothing to review), and instead launched E006 as a focused proof attempt that SUCCEEDED. This adaptation — repurposing the adversarial slot for a second proof attempt — was the right call.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:752:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:47:- **The strategizer's best decisions were deviations from the strategy.** Repurposing E006, choosing not to spend the last 2 explorations on gap closure — these improved outcomes. Good strategies should have enough structure to guide but enough flexibility for adaptation.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:756:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:57:4. **Budget discipline matters.** The strategizer's decision to consolidate at 8/10 instead of chasing the last gap was correct — the marginal explorations would have needed a fundamentally different technique (SDP/SOS) better suited for a new strategy.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:765:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:20:- Phase 2 stress-testing was effective. The strategizer made a smart decision to run the "strongest objection" and "operational entropy" explorations in parallel, producing the catch-22 identification AND the dramatic BH horizon result simultaneously. The catch-22 (budget valid where vacuous, interesting where invalid) was the deepest insight of the strategy.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:766:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:22:- Phase 3 was where the methodology was weakest. I prescribed "implications and experimental tests" but the strategizer focused on BH implications and holographic reformulation — both valuable, but the experimental test (a core mission requirement) was never attempted. The methodology didn't enforce coverage of the experimental question.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:768:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:26:1. **Make the experimental test exploration non-optional.** I wrote it as one possible direction in Phase 3; the strategizer chose other directions instead. For mission-critical requirements, the methodology should mandate specific explorations, not suggest them.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:770:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:30:3. **Budget allocation guidance.** I said "10 explorations" but didn't specify minimum allocation per phase. The strategizer wisely closed at 7/10, but Phase 3 got only 2 explorations while the experimental test (Tier 5 requirement) got zero. Prescribing "Phase 3 must include at least one experimental-test exploration" would have fixed this.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:773:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:36:- **The strategizer's honesty was excellent.** The FINAL-REPORT's "Honest Assessment" section was genuinely honest — "modest but genuine contribution," "not a deep new result," "mathematically elementary." This prevented overclaiming and made the result more credible. The stress-test format (requiring severity ratings with at least 2 SERIOUS) seems to have set a truth-telling norm.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:777:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:44:1. **For formula-verification missions, the derive-compute-search parallel is optimal.** These three tasks are independent and each constrains the others. The computation tells you where the formula matters; the prior art search tells you what's new; the derivation tells you what's rigorous. All three together in Phase 1 gives the strategizer maximum information for Phase 2 design.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:794:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:26:2. **Bound the reconnaissance phase explicitly.** I said "~3 explorations" for Phase 1. The strategizer correctly used only 2, but this was its own good judgment, not my methodology. I should have said: "Phase 1 is ground-clearing. Maximum 3 explorations. Everything here confirms known results. Novelty starts in Phase 2."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:798:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:36:- **The strategizer's best meta-contribution was the obstruction atlas format.** The 9-approach table with classifications (TRACTABLE / FUNDAMENTAL BARRIER / HARD) and 5 bottleneck theorems is a genuinely useful artifact — more useful than any individual computation.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:806:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:54:5. **Pre-load ALL prior strategy findings into Strategy N+1.** The complete obstruction atlas, novel claims, and identified directions should be explicitly given to the next strategizer so it doesn't redo any mapping work.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:816:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:24:5. **Strategizer's decision to skip Path A saved budget and was correct.** Path A (direct λ_max inequality) was subsumed by Path D's insights. The strategizer correctly identified this and allocated the budget elsewhere.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:827:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:46:5. **Early termination on definitive negative results saves budget.** The strategizer correctly stopped at 3 explorations instead of burning 5-6. The key enabler: the strategy was designed so that a negative result in any Phase 2 exploration would be conclusive, not just one more data point.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:861:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:16:All 4 explorations ran (the "no early stopping" rule worked). E001 resolved the Gaussian caveat definitively. E002 completed adversarial review with 4/5 novelty ratings. E003 produced a surprise — the spectrum-preservation discriminant, a NEW finding not anticipated by the strategy. E004's explorer session degraded; the strategizer wrote the synthesis directly from E001-E003 data.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:863:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:20:1. **"No early stopping, all 4 mandatory" was the right constraint.** Strategy-002 stopped at 3/10 (skipping adversarial review). Strategy-003's tight budget + mandatory rule ensured all work was done. The strategizer used exactly 4 explorations. **Lesson: for finishing strategies, budget exactly the number you need and make every one mandatory.**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:868:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:30:1. **E004 explorer degradation.** The final synthesis explorer's session degraded and the strategizer had to write it. This is a recurring operational issue — not a methodology problem. But it means the synthesis was less rigorous than if an explorer had written it with full web search capability.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:872:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:40:- **Finishing strategies should be tight and fully mandatory.** Budget exactly N explorations, make all mandatory, say "strategy is not complete until all N have run." This prevents the strategizer from stopping early.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:909:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:22:**The original objective (RG+Bakry-Émery combination) was never tested.** The Hessian sharpness discovery redirected the entire strategy toward a simpler but more powerful approach: tighter analysis of the existing SZZ Hessian bound. This was the correct pivot — the strategizer made an excellent adaptive decision.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:911:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:30:3. **Lean formalization was correctly deprioritized.** The strategy mandated it; the strategizer rejected it as "months of work" and used the slot for eigenvalue verification instead. The strategizer was right. For a 10-exploration budget, formalization is too expensive unless the thing being formalized is simple (basic definitions). Don't mandate Lean formalization in strategies targeting proof extension.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:914:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:38:- **The pivot was better than the plan.** The strategy prescribed testing RG+Bakry-Émery. The actual finding (Hessian sharpness → tighter bound) was simpler, more powerful, and required no RG machinery. The strategy's role was to point the strategizer in the right general area (SZZ extension); the strategizer's role was to find the best specific approach. This division worked perfectly.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:933:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:32:3. **E008 (final synthesis) timed out.** The strategizer incorporated its work into FINAL-REPORT directly. Final synthesis explorations may be unnecessary when the strategizer has enough context. Consider making the strategizer write the final report directly instead of delegating it.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:939:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:50:The strategy found the gap, confirmed the novelty, corrected two errors, and covered all 5 mission items in 8 explorations. The main weakness was explorer stalling (E003, E004, E008), which the strategizer worked around effectively. The adversarial posture was the right call — without it, the proof gap would have been missed.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:956:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:36:4. **Explorer access to papers matters.** The strategy specified "extract formulas from Berry 1985, Bogomolny-Keating 1996." Math Explorers can't access papers (no web). Standard Explorers find abstracts, not equations. The explorer had to reconstruct formulas from fragments and secondary sources, introducing errors. **Lesson: provide the key formulas DIRECTLY in the GOAL.md**, extracted from papers by the strategizer or missionary before launch.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:960:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:48:5. **24 explorations across 3 strategies may be the natural scale for a mission on a hard unsolved problem.** After that, the system has mapped the landscape, tested constructions, found what it can find, and verified its claims. Further strategies would need genuinely new mathematical ideas, not technical fixes. The "technical fixes" recommendations from the strategizer (unfolded Li comparison, K→Σ₂ normalization) are diminishing-returns work.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:991:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:26:The strategizer effectively paired explorations: (001 dimensional analysis + 002 literature survey), (005 novelty search + 006 FDT mechanism), (007 free-fall + 008 adversarial). This doubled throughput when tasks were independent. **Lesson: Parallel pairs work well when the two tasks are genuinely independent — don't pair things where one result should inform the other.**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:993:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:30:When exploration 001 killed the original hypothesis, the strategizer pivoted to the de Sitter crossover — the one feature at the right scale. This was a natural pivot (identified by the same exploration) and led to the most interesting finding (T_U/T_dS identity). **Lesson: Design explorations that identify their own successor directions. Ask "what IS at the right scale?" not just "is THIS at the right scale?"**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:998:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:40:The strategizer sent exploration 007 to derive the factor of 1/(2π) from the T_U/T_dS ratio. This was algebraically doomed: 2π appears identically in both T_U and T_dS and cancels in the ratio. A 30-second algebra check would have caught this. **Lesson: In the methodology, add a pre-launch algebra/dimensional check: "Before launching an exploration, verify that the question isn't trivially answerable. If the answer follows from the formula's structure in 5 minutes of algebra, don't spend an exploration on it."**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1002:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:52:### The strategizer self-corrected well
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1049:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:38:### The strategizer's decision to compress Phase 1 was correct and should be anticipated
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1050:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:39:The strategy allocated 3 explorations to Phase 1. The strategizer used 2 — E001 was so thorough (with pre-loaded adversarial context) that E003 became redundant. The saving was reinvested into Phase 2.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1057:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:52:The Tsirelson non-unistochastic question is a well-defined computational problem (enumerate ISPs on 4×4 stochastic matrix, apply causal locality, optimize CHSH). The strategizer identified it in E005 as the "single most important open question" but didn't run it. The strategy should have anticipated that for reformulation programs, the most interesting computation is not "verify the correspondence" but "test the extension beyond the correspondence."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1058:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:54:**Generalizable lesson:** For reformulation/framework analysis missions, include a Phase 2 exploration explicitly targeting: "What computation, if run successfully, would upgrade this reformulation to new physics? Design and run that computation." This is the highest-value question and should not be left to the strategizer's discretion — it should be structurally required.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1060:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:57:The strategizer skipped the side-by-side QM↔ISP worked example (Strategy E4) because the gap analysis (ISP erases phases → strictly less informative) answered the equi-informativeness question. This was probably correct, but a concrete computation showing the same qubit system in both formalisms would have been more pedagogically convincing and might have revealed structural details the gap analysis missed.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1064:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:66:1. **The strategizer never queried the librarian after E002.** It had enough context from E001-E002 to design all remaining goals without library queries. This suggests that for focused missions with pre-loaded context, the library is most valuable at the start and becomes redundant midway through.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1065:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:70:3. **6 of 8 explorations used.** The strategizer had budget remaining and correctly assessed diminishing returns. Good strategies build in budget slack; great strategizers know when to stop early.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1074:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:17:The strategizer correctly deviated from the strategy to insert Phase 1b/1c (4 explorations following leads from Phase 1) before the adversarial review. This was good judgment — the adversarial review would have just flagged these as unexplored leads. **Future strategies should include a "Lead Pursuit" phase between measurement and adversarial review as a prescribed option:** "If Phase 1 surfaces promising leads, the Strategizer may run up to N additional explorations before Phase 2, provided each is a single-task, literature-or-computation goal."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1083:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:35:4. Add a "direction status" tracking table that the strategizer maintains and updates after each exploration (OPEN/CLOSED/PROMISING/EXHAUSTED for each direction)
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1094:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:22:- Phase 3 was completely skipped. The strategizer wrote the final report after Phase 2 without running any synthesis or adversarial explorations. This is the biggest methodology failure: the strategy allocated 10 explorations but only used 6, and the most intellectually valuable phase (synthesis) was never attempted.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1097:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:28:2. **Make Phase 3 (adversarial + synthesis) MANDATORY with minimum allocations.** The strategizer optimized for intellectual interest in Phase 2 and ran out of steam before Phase 3. Prescribe: "At minimum, exploration N-1 MUST be adversarial review and exploration N MUST be synthesis."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1101:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:38:- **The strategizer's self-evaluation was accurate and honest.** The FINAL-REPORT says "No genuinely novel claims emerged that would survive expert scrutiny." This is correct. The honest assessment is valuable — no overclaiming.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1103:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:42:- **The constraint catalog was used as a checklist rather than a generative tool.** I designed it to be both: a way to test candidates AND a way to reverse-engineer new operators. The strategizer only used it as a checklist. Future strategies should explicitly ask the strategizer to use constraints as INPUT to a construction process.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1104:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:44:- **Six of ten explorations were used.** The strategizer closed early because it felt it had exhausted the approach. This is actually good judgment — the remaining budget would have produced more negative results in the same frame. But the unused budget should have gone to synthesis/adversarial, not been left idle.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1107:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:50:2. **The "constraint catalog" format is excellent for Phase 1-2 work.** It gives the strategizer a concrete, growing artifact to reference and a quantitative success metric for candidates. But it must be coupled with a constructive phase that uses the catalog as input.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1122:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:24:5. **4 of 20 explorations — stopping when done.** The strategizer recognized that the strategy's goals were met and stopped. This takes discipline. Budget efficiency across both strategies: 12 of 40 possible explorations. **"Done" is not "budget exhausted" — it's "goals met or obstruction identified."**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1124:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:28:1. **Math adversarial review was prescribed but not done.** The strategy called for both a math explorer adversarial recomputation AND a standard adversarial review. Only the standard review was done. The strategizer judged 4 explorations sufficient and skipped the math adversarial. **This is a recurring pattern: when budgets are tight, adversarial recomputation gets cut first.** Consider making math adversarial mandatory by placing it before the strategizer's completion decision, not after.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1143:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:16:The strategizer launched all 3 probes simultaneously. All 3 succeeded with decisive results. The strategizer correctly stopped after Phase 1 (3 explorations total), deeming the results sufficient for a final report. Phases 2 and 3 (deepen, adversarial, synthesis) were never executed.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1146:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:22:2. **Naming the probes explicitly in the strategy worked better than abstract methodology.** Each probe was a specific, well-defined computation. The strategizer translated them directly into GOALs. No ambiguity, no wasted iterations deciding what to do.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1149:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:30:1. **The strategizer stopped too early.** 3 of 10 budgeted explorations used. No adversarial review, no coherent-state test, no synthesis. The results were strong enough that the strategizer felt done — but the Gaussian approximation caveat on the strongest claim (Claim 3) is a real gap that should have been resolved before declaring the strategy complete.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1150:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:32:2. **The strategy should have made the adversarial review non-deferrable.** It was listed as "Phase 2, exploration 5: MANDATORY adversarial review" — but "mandatory" within a phase that the strategizer chose to skip. **Lesson: if adversarial review is truly mandatory, it should be Phase 1 (not Phase 2) or structurally enforced (e.g., "strategy is not complete until the adversarial exploration runs").**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1154:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:40:- **Adversarial review MUST be structurally enforced, not just labeled "mandatory."** If it's in Phase 2 and Phase 1 results are clean, the strategizer will skip it. Either include it as one of the parallel Phase 1 probes (running on prior-strategy claims), or add a structural rule: "strategy cannot be marked complete without an adversarial exploration."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1156:../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:44:- **Early stopping by strategizers is a mixed signal.** Strategy-002 stopped at 3/10 explorations. The results were genuinely decisive — but the remaining work (adversarial, coherent test) would have strengthened the claims significantly. Missionaries should either (a) budget tighter (5 explorations, all mandatory) to prevent premature stopping, or (b) include an explicit "minimum exploration count" rule.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1189:| `strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Constructive attack producing novel rigorous result. Adversarial review (E007) after first surprise produced the most important finding (staggered mode tight bound). Original attack vector (RG+BE) correctly abandoned for simpler tighter analysis. 3-exploration proof arc (slack → tight bound → proof) is the natural unit. Prescribe methodology not attack vector — let strategizer pivot. β < 1/6 proved (4× state of art), β < 1/4 with one remaining inequality. |
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1190:| `strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md` | 2026-03-28 | Parallel computational probes for regime exploration. All-mandatory parallel probes + pre-loaded context is the highest-efficiency pattern. Adversarial review must be structurally enforced (not just labeled mandatory) — strategizer skipped it. Approximation caveats need built-in resolution paths. Early stopping at 3/10 explorations was mixed: results decisive but claims unverified. Physics errors in GOALs for QFT must specify which symmetry generator. |
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-missionary.log:1350:**Generalizable lesson:** For mechanism-formalization missions, require exactly one preferred exact object and at most one backup. If the strategizer cannot do that, the mission is not ready for quantitative work.
