runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1192:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-navier-stokes-learnings.md:30:2. **Literature survey should have preceded the spectral Ladyzhenskaya computation.** Exploration 006 (spectral Ladyzhenskaya) was predictably a dead end if you read Tao (2014). The strategizer recognized this in hindsight. **When a direction depends on whether harmonic analysis alone can improve things, check for known obstructions FIRST.**
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1299:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/methodology/INDEX.md:56:- **check-bypass-not-just-improve-bottleneck.md** — NEW (vasseur-pressure S2-E005): When a bottleneck tool limits progress, always ask "can we avoid this tool entirely?" before "can we improve it?" Protocol: (1) Can we avoid using this tool at all? (2) Is there a fundamentally different tool for the same job? (3) Can we improve the tool's output? S2-E001 through S2-E005 spent 5 explorations on question 3 (improving CZ or working around it); the strategizer should have asked question 1 after S2-E001 showed all CZ-based routes are tight. Distinct from ask-what-replaces-the-bottleneck (what new bottleneck after reformulation vs. whether to use the tool at all), decomposition-audit-before-attacking-barrier (which step is tight vs. whether the framework is right), and decisive-negative-pivot (when to stop vs. what direction to go).
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1332:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/goal-design/verify-goal-claims-before-delegating.md:57:- **vasseur-pressure exploration-003** — Goal referenced "Tran-Yu (2014, AIHP)" which does not exist. The actual program is 5 papers (2015-2021). The explorer recovered by searching systematically, but it cost exploration time. The strategizer/missionary should verify paper existence before prescribing specific citations in GOAL.md.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1342:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/goal-design/adversarial-synthesis-goal-structure.md:67:**[vasseur-pressure S2-E007]** When the adversarial review evaluates multiple novel claims, require a ranked list by publishability with per-claim scores for correctness, novelty, significance, and standalone publishability. This format immediately tells the strategizer what to formalize next. S2-E007: ranked list (Claim 3 > Claim 2 > Claim 4 > Claim 1 > Claim 5) directly prioritized formalizing the seven-route obstruction over the universal formula. Include "fatal flaw?" column — some claims score high on novelty/significance but have a fundamental limitation (e.g., informal rather than rigorous). Include "most publishable combination" assessment — individual claims may be unpublishable but strong in combination.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1343:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/goal-design/adversarial-synthesis-goal-structure.md:71:**[vasseur-pressure S2-E007]** Adversarial reviews should propose the most actionable formalization step for informal claims, not just identify weaknesses. "This claim needs work" produces paralysis; "here's how to make it rigorous" enables action. S2-E007: identifying the SDP approach (sum-of-squares relaxation to find optimal |{|u| > lambda}| bound given NS constraints) as the specific formalization path for the informal sharpness claim was the most actionable output of the entire adversarial review. Protocol: for each claim rated below VERIFIED, propose one specific formalization method (SDP, counterexample search, formal definition, etc.) with enough detail that the strategizer can write a GOAL.md.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1351:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/goal-design/INDEX.md:38:- **verify-goal-claims-before-delegating.md** — **[NEW, YM s003-meta-005/s003-007]** Before writing GOAL.md citing a prior result (e.g., "M(Q) ≼ M(I) confirmed by E004"), verify the cited claim actually matches what the exploration found. Two-level fix: (1) strategizer re-reads REPORT.md before citing; (2) GOAL.md includes "first compute X for 3-5 random examples — if it fails, pivot." Prevented two wasted explorations in yang-mills s003. **NEW variant: "verify paper existence before citing"** [vasseur-pressure E003 — "Tran-Yu (2014, AIHP)" doesn't exist; actual program is 5 papers 2015-2021]. Distinct from preload-context (providing findings) and include-trivial-control-checks (validating code).
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1360:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/goal-design/specify-rigor-level.md:27:- **"Is X better than Y?"** — When the paper itself may directly answer a comparative question (e.g., "is β₀(4) > 1/24?"), ask it as a direct comparison rather than asking for descriptions of each in isolation. The paper's Remark or comparison section will often give the definitive answer. Produces a forced verdict that the strategizer can act on immediately.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1527:- **stochastic-electrodynamics strategy-001 exploration 001** — The strategizer pointed the explorer
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1558:- **riemann-hypothesis strategy-003 exploration-006** — The GOAL.md template specified weight = (log p)² for Berry's diagonal approximation, but the correct Berry (1985) weight is (log p)²/p^m. The 1/p^m factor comes from the squared semiclassical amplitude |A_{p,m}|². Without it, K_primes was ~183 at τ=1 (should be ~1). The explorer caught and corrected this, but it cost debugging time. The strategizer should have checked Berry's original formula before writing the weight expression.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1564:- **stochastic-electrodynamics strategy-002 exploration-005** — The GOAL.md code snippet included `omega_max=10.0` as a function parameter but the PSD formula body computed `S_F = 2*tau*hbar*omegas**3/m` without the `np.where(..., omegas <= omega_max, ...)` guard. This meant the "no-cutoff" version ran, producing A ≈ 1.6 instead of the correct A ≈ 1.07 (the E001 value). The explorer caught this by re-reading the original E001 code and comparing it line-by-line to the goal template — costing extra time. Had the strategizer tested the template against one known result before pasting it, the bug would have been caught at goal-writing time.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1591:When a follow-up exploration needs to build on prior results, have the explorer **re-read the actual saved data files** (e.g., `.npz`, `.pkl`, prior REPORT.md) rather than relying on the strategizer's summary of those results. Strategizer summaries can contain transcription errors, incorrect parameter descriptions, or wrong reference values that waste exploration time.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:1969:- **check-bypass-not-just-improve-bottleneck.md** — NEW (vasseur-pressure S2-E005): When a bottleneck tool limits progress, always ask "can we avoid this tool entirely?" before "can we improve it?" Protocol: (1) Can we avoid using this tool at all? (2) Is there a fundamentally different tool for the same job? (3) Can we improve the tool's output? S2-E001 through S2-E005 spent 5 explorations on question 3 (improving CZ or working around it); the strategizer should have asked question 1 after S2-E001 showed all CZ-based routes are tight. Distinct from ask-what-replaces-the-bottleneck (what new bottleneck after reformulation vs. whether to use the tool at all), decomposition-audit-before-attacking-barrier (which step is tight vs. whether the framework is right), and decisive-negative-pivot (when to stop vs. what direction to go).
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:2210:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:42:- **The constraint catalog was used as a checklist rather than a generative tool.** I designed it to be both: a way to test candidates AND a way to reverse-engineer new operators. The strategizer only used it as a checklist. Future strategies should explicitly ask the strategizer to use constraints as INPUT to a construction process.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:2211:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:50:2. **The "constraint catalog" format is excellent for Phase 1-2 work.** It gives the strategizer a concrete, growing artifact to reference and a quantitative success metric for candidates. But it must be coupled with a constructive phase that uses the catalog as input.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:2226:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/meta/goal-design/specify-rigor-level.md:27:- **"Is X better than Y?"** — When the paper itself may directly answer a comparative question (e.g., "is β₀(4) > 1/24?"), ask it as a direct comparison rather than asking for descriptions of each in isolation. The paper's Remark or comparison section will often give the definitive answer. Produces a forced verdict that the strategizer can act on immediately.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:2289:- **thermal-time strategy-001 meta-exploration-001** — Exploration-001 combined a modular Hamiltonian catalog (paper-reading + formalization) with a Fock-space computation. The normalization question (τ=t vs. τ=β·t) arose mid-exploration and was correctly flagged as open rather than resolved — which required a dedicated follow-up exploration (E002). The strategizer note: "When the key question is normalization (a convention question), put it in its own exploration — it requires careful paper-reading that competes with computation time."
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall-strategy-001-curator-002.log:2304:**Relationship to one-task-per-exploration:** This corollary is the pragmatic fallback for when the strategizer nevertheless includes multiple tasks. The ideal is one task; the next best is explicit skip permissions.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:875:- The initially launched explorer stalled after writing only placeholder report files. Manual recovery by the strategizer was straightforward because the relevant local evidence had already been narrowed by the receptionist and preloaded before launch.
runtime/logs/codex-atlas-exact-ns-tiny-trigger-firewall-strategy-001-curator-001.log:1417:- **allow-explorer-synthesis.md** — Don't over-specify conclusions; specify what to investigate and what format to produce, but leave synthesis conclusions open. Explorers can discover structural patterns (e.g., two-tier tree-vs-loop insight; N²/p ≈ 250-310 ratio; underexploited constraints insight; unexpected no-go theorems) the strategizer didn't anticipate — often the most valuable outputs. **NEW variant: "What would be a breakthrough?" primes explorer for high-value output** without specifying what the answer should be. **NEW variant: "Explain WHY this agrees with [prior result]" elicits novel bonus derivations** — the mechanism explanation is more valuable than the consistency check itself (SED s003-meta-001: symmetry argument from P&C consistency check).
